rComments: Mr Shishir Shahnawaz is awesome. He is very accommodating but isn't the best lecturer so be prepared to work for your grade. Projects isn't even a easy class anyways but he brought in some good guest lecturers and extended deadlines all the time. Shishir Shahnawaz for prime minister!
Helpful but a bit annoying especially when a question is asked and he goes overboard. Gentle and very accommodating.

He was available outside lecture hours, and helped me answer my questions. His lectures are heavy and he expects everyone in his class to come prepared. Some of his reading materials were too loaded with postgrad stuff.
Good, but a tough grader.

Professor Shahnawaz cares for his students. He has specific guidelines, gives you the questions that will be on the midterm, and the lectures are decently interesting. The only downside - he randomly picks on people! (and there is an attendance sheet)

Hard-rater but soft-spoken. Caring but critical. At times, it was difficult for me to read this prof. Perhaps, I was overloaded with my work, but I know for sure he knew about it for one and for all. He is not as problematic as other profs in the department. responds email even at 3 or 4 am.

Professor Shishir is gentle and was sympathetic to my personal health problems. He allowed me a delayed submission and was constantly in touch to know if I needed any help. He expects us to read a lot, which may have some downsides especially when his lectures were too loaded, and at times he forgot to review what was asked of us.

He is a good person, no doubt! I guess he works in the Government. His slides reflect he is neat at work. Lot of take-home readings which made me crazy. In the end, he is nice and wrote me a strong letter of reference for my grad admission.

He is surely one of those profs who like to see you slog. Not recommended if you take 4 or more courses in a semester, as he is surely going to make you work hard. Good luck with an abundance of reading.

Read assigned articles + participate in class discussion (talk, talk, talk)  You are in good books Reading is painful, some of the articles are outdated. Good marker, and a great recommender for grad school
Knowledgeable, but he makes you work hard. Students are randomly picked up and then asked to present a topic from a long reading list. Its embarrassing, as he points that out in the class.

Worst prof I've ever had. Makes things out to seem a lot harder than they are. Doesn't take responsibility for his mistakes. ( Class was waiting 45min because he was late to a mid term- and then said that he did it on purpose because ONE student asked him to?). The TA had no idea of this and decided to call him. Found out that he was in a meeting.

Mr. Shahnawaz is a really good professor. He is a fair marker when it comes to evaluations. Really interesting subject matter. Be prepared to read around 30 pages per week. Participation is a must as well as group projects. Evaluations include few quizzes, midterm, documentary review and essay and documentary review for the final. Awesome class.
Very unclear

Good prof. He introduces interesting materials in the class, and shares his personal experience on International Development issues with students. Somewhat of a hard marker! However, he is happy to review any reasonable claim and adjust grades if necessary. His instructions in the syllabus are tricky. That said, pay close attention to his instructi

Take his courses at your discretion (for a good reason). He will expect you to be a critical thinker, problem solver, and team worker. He bases his scores on these and he will find out if you are worth these!
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Participation matters', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: He is always there to help students develop competencies for his class, but one needs to have a knack for it. One thing for sure, he sets high expectation. If you are not near that, it gets tough to score well. He memorizes everyones name in the first 2-3 weeks, and then monitors everyones progress throughout the semester. TAs work at his command

This prof is a tough grader. He usually talks a lot in his class, mostly from his own field experience. It's ideal if you come prepared to his class, and you will find his lectures meaningful. The only problem is the rules he already lays down in the syllabus. He usually does not relax those rules for any students. Good luck taking his class.

This professor is not worth taking classes with. He is very unclear with how he will mark, and he never leaves any comments on assignments or the midterm, so good luck figuring out how to improve. Personally, he is nice enough (usually) to go talk to, but as a professor, he's just awful.

All he cares about is that you attend his lecture regularly; come to his class prepared (he has a long list of recommended readings for each class and he randomly picks up students to address issues), you submit your work in time, and you present your work neatly! Bingo … score an “A” !

He is strict with deadlines. He doesn’t like students messing around with his assignment questions prior to deadlines and he believes in “Do or Die” policy. He is very professional in his appointments.

Positive – caring and makes lessons meaningful Negative – not attentive to details (I used to take his appointments to discuss issues of my concerns and interests which he never entertained in the class – although most of those issues are general in nature)

Technically sound. He has an eagle`s eye to pick up inconsistency in your work. Bottomline: do your work professionally and allow a lot of time to ensure quality. You are safe that way. Students who understand this compete with each other and eventually attain comparable scores (``A-`` and ``A``s).
The best thing I like about this professor is that he is very encouraging. The worst thing is that he takes time to respond to my emails. Overall, he is caring and has a listening attitude.

He has a solid background and he is conceptually sound in research methods. The metaphors he uses are too good. He builds the base for research methods. One caution, if you have a critical question about any concept, better discuss with him personally as he at times gets too technical and wordy which bug other people not interested in details.

The king of BS. However, he is quite funny and knowledgeable on a number of topics related to DVM. Follow the rubrics exactly, follow his instructions and you will do really well. When you ask him a question, take some time to think about his answer before leaving, chances are he gave a vague answer but would be willing to give you a better one.

Although easygoing, he knows his stuff well. So better not argue if you didn't prepare the lessons. He'll easily find out that you didn't study and that you showed up in his class for attendance. He expects you to read recommended materials before you'd appear in his class. He has a habit of randomly picking up students in his lessons.GOOD LUCK (y)

A great prof. and is very caring. Meets students outside office hours. One can score well by following his instructions on assignments. He has a “to-do” list for students; watch out for those in his syllabus.

I really enjoyed his class “Globalization” in the summer’13. His assignments are tricky. Read between the lines on the assignment questions & you'll be ok. He puts in effort in teaching and gives a lot of notes so be prepared to write. He tells his students exactly what he expects and doesn't take anything less. Nice person! I would take him again!

This prof has some unique teaching styles. He comes into the class, makes eye contacts with all, and then starts telling a story (mostly narratives). He then begins to relate the story to the lecture topic of the day. Dr. Shahnawaz uses great metaphors and it’s quite helpful for me to prepare for my midterm by simply reviewing his class notes.

Dr. Shishir has a unique teaching methodology. He blends theory with practice - which I find really important for students in international development. His comments on my assignments are really helpful. Although he takes time to respond emails; I guess he makes sure he guides students properly. Best part, he meets students beyond his office hours.
